data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new **span overload resolution rules**. Your `array.Contains(num)` now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based methods, so this throws at runtime.

## Fix

Force the compiler to pick the `Enumerable` overload by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

This applies to **any expression tree** calling `.Contains()`, `.Reverse()`, or similar LINQ methods on arrays — C# 14's span conversions cause the span overload to win. Use `.AsEnumerable()`, explicit casts, or static `Enumerable.*` calls throughout.
